# Git Commands #

git init: Initializes a new Git repository in the current directory.
git status: Displays the status of the working directory and staging area, showing changes that are staged, unstaged, or untracked.
git add <file>: Stages specified files for commit.
git commit -m "<message>": Commits the staged changes with a message.
git log: Shows the commit history.
git config --global user.name "<name>" and git config --global user.email "<email>": Sets the global user name and email for Git commits.
git branch: Lists or manages branches in the repository.
git checkout <branch>: Switches to the specified branch.
git checkout -b <branch>: Creates and switches to a new branch.
git log --oneline: Shows a compact view of the commit history.

# Linux User and Group Management Commands #

useradd <username>: Creates a new user.
passwd <username>: Sets or changes the password for the specified user.
userdel <username>: Deletes a user.
groupadd <groupname>: Creates a new group.
gpasswd -a <user> <group>: Adds a user to a group.
cat /etc/passwd: Displays user account details.
cat /etc/group: Displays group information.
File Management and Permissions Commands
touch <filename>: Creates an empty file.
mv <source> <destination>: Renames or moves a file or directory.
chmod <permissions> <file>: Changes the file permissions.
chown <user> <file>: Changes the owner of the specified file.
chgrp <group> <file>: Changes the group ownership of a file.
ls -la: Lists files in the directory with detailed information, including hidden files.

# System Navigation and Directory Management #

cd <directory>: Changes the current directory.
ls: Lists files and directories.
pwd: Prints the current working directory.
su <user>: Switches to another user account.
